{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/7-numpy-tricks-to-make-my-code-better-and-smarter-9e8a4ccf43d1", "time": 1683013916.184909, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/7-numpy-tricks-to-make-my-code-better-and-smarter-9e8a4ccf43d1/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "7 Numpy Tricks to Make My Code Better and Smarter | by C K | Towards Data Science", "h1": "7 Numpy Tricks to Make My Code Better and Smarter", "description": "Numpy is one of the most important and popular libraries in Python for numerical computation. It is widely used in data science and machine learning, a lot of libraries are built on top of it. I wish\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["Numpy is one of the most important and popular libraries in Python for numerical computation. It is widely used in data science and machine learning, a lot of libraries are built on top of it. I wish to share 7 Numpy tricks that I wish I had known earlier as a beginner in this post.", "np.linespace(start, stop, num) return an array with the evenly spaced numbers from strat to stop", "It is convenient to draw math function:", "np.arange(start, stop, step) provides similar function, it creates an array from start to stop in step.", "It is quite often we need to generate random numbers for statical calculation. Numpy offers some functions to generate random numbers.", "randint(low, high, size) generates an array (size=size) of random integers in the range (low \u2014 high).", "rand() generates random numbers uniformly distributed between 0 to 1 in a given shape.", "randn() generates random numbers in a normal distribution.", "random.choice() allows us to randomly choose samples from a given array. It is also possible to pass a probability.", "np.argmax() returns the indices of the maximum values along an axis.", "It is useful in object classification and detection to find the object with the highest probability.", "There are also similar functions like argmin() , argwhere() , argpartition()", "np.setdiff1d() returns the values in an array that are not in another array.", "For example, we have two arrays:", "If we want to find the values in athat are not presented in b(the answer should be [1,2,3]), we can use setdiff1d() :", "We can also do it the other way around, finding values in b that are not presented in a:", "One similar function is intersect1d() , it returns the intersection of 2 arrays, which is [4,5,6] in this case.", "np.where(condition,x,y) returns elements chosen from x or y depending on condition.", "For example, we have an array containing exam scores:", "We want to replace the scores by \u2018pass\u2019 or \u2018not_pass\u2019. The condition can be set as scores>60 :", "If the x and y are not passed to the np.where , the index position of the elements that meet the condition will be returned.", "Sometimes we need to reshape the array, we can use the resphape() method.", "For example, we have a one dimension array:", "We can reshape it to a 2x5 array:", "We can use -1 , numpy calculates the dimension for you.", "If you want to reshape a multidimensional array to 1D array, you can use flatten()", "You can also stack multiple arrays in one array using np.stack() .", "You can do it among other axis,", "You can also use hstack() to stack arrays horizontally:", "If you have an array containing some numbers and a range, you can use clip() to limit the numbers to that range. For numbers outside the range, it returns the edge value.", "It clips the array between 3 to 5.", "That\u2019s it. These Numpy tricks make my code a lot simpler and efficient. I hope these help you too", "I also wrote articles about Python and Pandas. You can take a look if you are interested.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F9e8a4ccf43d1&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_la